"To be honorable, you have to make sacrifices for others.\n\n- Sunday Adelaja, The Mountain of Ignorance\n|\nWhere there has been true science, art has always been its exponent.\n\n- Leo Tolstoy, On the Significance of Science and Art\n|\nThat is what you meant to me: a light that shone through the darkness.” (Your smile, p. 56)\n\n- Chimnese Davids, Muses of Wandering Passions\n|\nIf those who are sent to draw water begin by drinking themselves, the army is suffering from thirst. [One may know the condition of a whole army from the behavior of a single man.]\n\n- Sun Tzu, The Art of War\n|\nsomething was dead in each of us,and what was dead was hope.\n\n- Oscar Wilde, The Ballad Of Reading Gaol\n|\nThis must be Thursday,' said Arthur to himself, sinking low over his beer. 'I never could get the hang of Thursdays.\n\n- Douglas Adams, The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy\n|\nNobody has ever measured, not even poets, how much the heart can hold.\n\n- Zelda\n|\nI love new clothes. If everyone could just wear new clothes everyday, I reckon depression wouldn’t exist anymore.\n\n- Sophie Kinsella, Confessions of a Shopaholic\n|\nThe place we get lost is the very place that we're found, all we need to do is put one foot in front of the other.\n\n- Steph Jagger, Unbound: A Story of Snow and Self-Discovery\n|\nI cannot afford to lose you, too''You cannot lose something you do not own. Take me with you\n\n- Kiersten White, And I Darken\n|\nReject anything advice, which does not lead to your personal progress.\n\n- Lailah Gifty Akita, Think Great: Be Great!\n|\nMaturity is a bitter disappointment for which no remedy exists, unless laughter could be said to remedy anything.\n\n- Kurt\n|\nYou'll never reach perfection because there's always room for improvement. Yet get along the way to perfection, you'll learn to get better.\n\n- Hlovate, Versus\n|\nAnd the great question for mankind is what is to be loved or hated next, whenever and old love or fear has lost its hold.\n\n- Eugen Rosenstock-Huessy, Out of Revolution: Autobiography of Western Man\n|\nWhen I discover who I am, I’ll be free.\n\n- Ralph Ellison, Invisible Man\n|\nWhen I saw you I fell in love, and you smiled because you knew.\n\n- Arrigo\n|\nIf the partridge didn't call at the wrong moment, Neither the hunter nor the falcon would know of it. It follows from this point also, That everyone's voice betrays him.\n\n- Rahman Baba, The Poetry of Rahman Baba: Poet of the Pakhtuns\n|\nTechnology is neutral. But the process of technology will cause a free world to become ever freer, and a totalitarian world to become ever more repressive.\n\n- Ma Boyong, Invisible Planets: Contemporary Chinese Science Fiction in Translation\n|\nEvery great cause begins as a movement, becomes a business, and eventually degenerates into a racket.\n\n- Eric Hoffer, The Temper of Our Time\n|\nThe ego relies on the familiar. It is reluctant to experience the unknown, which is they very essence of life.\n\n- Deepak Chopra, The Third Jesus: The Christ We Cannot Ignore\n|\nWere you planning to jump off?'“Not on pizza day. Never on pizza day, which is one of the better days of the week.” I should mention that I am a brilliant deflector.\n\n- Jennifer Niven, All The Bright Places\n|\nIn this walk to freedom, we must, without question obtain hearts of honesty and a tongue of truthfulness.\n\n- The Tru Sum, Excerpts To Exodus\n|\nAll the time you're saying to yourself, 'I could do that, but I won't,' — which is just another way of saying that you can't.\n\n- Richard Feynman, Surely You're Joking, Mr. Feynman!: Adventures of a Curious Character\n|\nWriting a book is a herculean task, but the toughest thing is to get convinced with your work, and finally give it a green signal.\n\n- Shivam Chaudhary, An Intellectual\n|\nHe thought she knew what he meant, but the biggest mistake you can make is thinking they know what you mean.\n\n- Daniel Handler, Adverbs\n|\nIn the calculus of feelings, you never really know how one person's absence will affect you more than another's.\n\n- Gayle Forman, Where She Went\n|\nThe day she was born,her grandfather made her a ring of silver and a polished stone, because he loved her already.\n\n- Aliki\n|\nEveryone has his own reality in which, if one is not too cautious, timid or frightened, one swims. This is the only reality there is.\n\n- Henry Miller, Stand Still Like the Hummingbird\n|\nA truth should exist,it should not be usedlike this. If I love youis that a fact or a weapon?\n\n- Margaret\n|\nAll good things are powerful stimulants to life, even a good book written against life.\n\n- Friedrich Nietzsche, Human, All Too Human\n|\nTime is that by which at every moment all things become as nothing in our hands, and thereby lose all their true value.\n\n- Arthur\n|\nWhen the spirit is happy, the soul is full of smiles.\n\n- Lailah\n|\nThere's joy in every circumstance. The beginning is bitter, but in between, there are valuable lessons that bring joy.\n\n- WISDOM\n|\nI’d volunteer to go to prison, as long as there are books. Because with books I am free.\n\n- Mohammad\n|\nI've had a lot of worries in my life, most of which never happened.\n\n- Mark\n|\nD'you think he would have thought ahead like that?' said Henry. 'Assuredly,' said Will. 'The man's a strategist.' He tapped his temple. 'Like me.\n\n- Cassandra Clare, Clockwork Prince\n|\nThe secret to lifelong friendship is to treat is not just as a gift, but also as a responsibility. Thanks for playing your part to perfection....\n\n- Sachin\n|\nHe does something to me, that boy. Every time. It’s his only detriment. He steps on my heart. He makes me cry.\n\n- Markus Zusak, The Book Thief\n|\nYesterday was a closed book, tomorrow, however, was another story.\n\n- Cecelia Ahern, The Book of Tomorrow\n|\nTo act upon the outer world and change it, you must be first be fine to act upon yourself.\n\n- Grace Sara, Awakening in the 21st Century: Surviving a Spiritually Dormant Society\n|\nNo, officer, I have no idea why I'm wearing this possum costume. I called you what? OH. My bad.'-Nastasya\n\n- Cate Tiernan, Darkness Falls\n|\nI love you. I love you, but I’m turning to my versesand my heart is closinglike a fist.\n\n- Frank O'Hara, Meditations in an Emergency\n|\nArise, awake, stop not till the goal is reached.\n\n- Swami Vivekananda, Meditation and Its Methods According to Swami Vivekananda\n|\nIf knowledge is power, let's spread it as widely as possible and dilute it to deny those who would abuse it.\n\n- Stuart\n|\nFate isn’t one straight road…there are forks in it, many different routes to different ends. We have the free will to choose the path.\n\n- Dean Koontz, Odd Thomas\n|\nKnowledge comes, but wisdom lingers.\n\n- Alfred\n|\nMarriage without struggle is like an unfired clay pot.It is easily made, but it will not stand the test of time.\n\n- Allan Wolf, The Watch That Ends the Night\n|\nIf only we'd stop trying to be happy, we could have a pretty good time.\n\n- Edith\n|\nIf you have the power to change the world for the better, you should do it. That's why people who do nothing are idiots, but idiots who do nothing are life-savers.\n\n- James\n|\nIn order to have great happiness, you have to have great pain and unhappiness-otherwise how would you know when you're happy?\n\n- Leslie\n|\nIf you allow any minute of your time to pass without converting it into products, you will soon realize that you just wasted a part of your life.\n\n- Sunday Adelaja, How To Become Great Through Time Conversion: Are you wasting time, spending time or investing time?\n|\nReal courage is doing the right thing when nobody's looking. Doing the unpopular thing because it's what you believe, and the heck with everybody.\n\n- Justin Cronin, The Summer Guest\n|\nIt's an odd thing, but anyone who disappears is said to be seen in San Francisco.It must be a delightful city and possess all the attractions of the next world\n\n- Oscar\n|\nAs with all matters of ht heart, the odds may not be in our favour but it is the only risk worth taking.\n\n- Kaushik Ram, Hidden World: The Inside Story of the Soul\n|\nIn hindsight, events seem logical\n\n- Don Norman, The Design of Everyday Things\n|\nLet children read whatever they want and then talk about it with them. If parents and kids can talk together, we won't have as much censorship because we won't have as much fear.\n\n- Judy\n|\nGod does not patch up the old life,or make certain repairs on the old life;He gives a new life, through the new birth.\n\n- Kathryn\n|\nPretend that every single person you meet has a sign around his or her neck that says, 'Make me feel important.' Not only will you succeed in sales, you will succeed in life.\n\n- Mary\n|\nIt is no worse, because I write of it. It would be no better, if I stopped my most unwilling hand. Nothing can undo it; nothing can make it otherwise than as it was.\n\n- Charles Dickens, David Copperfield\n|\nLike the sun, a teacher enlightens a mind with his love, warmth, and light.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nEven a book can be dangerous in the wrong hands, and when that happens, you blame the hands, but you also read the book.\n\n- Erika Johansen, The Queen of the Tearling\n|\nFear is the venom impact of predator sting, causing prey not to be focus on the survival.\n\n- Toba Beta, My Ancestor Was an Ancient Astronaut\n|\nEncourage, lift and strengthen one another. For the positive energy spread to one will be felt by us all. For we are connected, one and all.\n\n- Deborah\n|\nIn the end, we all lose it. Remember that. In the end, we own nothing.\n\n- Richard Paul Evans, Miles to Go\n|\nThere is nothing new under the sun, but there are new suns.\n\n- Octavia\n|\nAnybody can Earn and Die, leaving a will and legacy. Only the courageous ones can give away all they have while they are Alive.\n\n- RVM\n|\nLast time I saw you, I said that it hurt too much to love you. But I was wrong about that. The truth is it hurts too much not to love you.\n\n- P.C.\n|\nKeep your eyes and your mind open. Don’t be blinded by filters like fear, uncertainty, pessimism and negativity.\n\n- Carlos Wallace, The Other 99 T.Y.M.E.S: Train Your Mind to Enjoy Serenity\n|\nCertain bookworms eat books. Eat them, swear in them, spill things on them.\n\n- Tara\n|\nAlthough I was able to maintain a pleasant expression, I was mentally throwing up in her face.\n\n- Augusten\n|\nWe make messes of our lives, but every now and then, we manage to do something that's exactly right. The challenge is figuring out which is which.\n\n- Jodi Picoult, Vanishing Acts\n|\nWhat are you going to do? 'Can't say - run for president, write -' 'Greenwich Village?' 'Good heavens, no - I said write - not drink.\n\n- F. Scott Fitzgerald, This Side of Paradise\n|\nSomeone once told me that we move when it becomes less painful than staying where we are'.\n\n- Anne Hines, The Spiral Garden\n|\nI like to write when I feel spiteful. It is like having a good sneeze.', November 1913)\n\n- D.H. Lawrence, Letters\n|\nBetray a friend, and you'll often find you have ruined yourself.\n\n- Aesop, Aesop's Fables\n|\nWe are a little land. And little lands on the borders of a great empire were always hateful to the lords of the great empire. He longs to blot them out, gobble them up.\n\n- C.S. Lewis, The Horse and His Boy\n|\nNo two readers can or will ever read the same book, because the reader builds the book in collaboration with the author.\n\n- Neil Gaiman, The View from the Cheap Seats: Selected Nonfiction\n|\nDead, we are revealed in our true dimensions, and they are surprisingly modest.\n\n- Michael Cunningham, The Hours\n|\nSo wise so young, they say, do never live long.\n\n- William Shakespeare, Richard III\n|\nAccept whatever comes to you woven in the pattern of your destiny, for what could more aptly fit your needs?\n\n- Marcus Aurelius, Meditations\n|\nMan…who lives in three places – in the past, in the present, and in the future – can be unhappy if one of these three is worthless. Religion has even added a fourth – eternity.\n\n- Georg\n|\nSometimes, the simple things are more fun and meaningful than all the banquets in the world ...\n\n- E.A. Bucchianeri, Brushstrokes of a Gadfly\n|\nHave faith in God and in yourself; that will cure all. Hope for the best, expect the best, toil for the best and everything will come right for you in the end.\n\n- Ramana\n|\nYour true potential is unlimited, and you can certainly achieve much more than human intelligence can comprehend.\n\n- Mensah\n|\nHe who exercises wisdom, exercises the knowledge which is about God.\n\n- Epictetus, Enchiridion and Selections from the Discourses\n|\nAll it takes, is a little spark...\n\n- Karen Laffey, 7 Ways to Feel Better Right Now\n|\nPersonally, I don’t like inherently happy people. I don’t trust them. I think there’s something seriously wrong with anyone who isn’t at least a little let down by the world.\n\n- Tiffanie DeBartolo, How to Kill a Rock Star\n|\nNever stand on one spot, always be doing something in line with your calling\n\n- Sunday\n|\nIf you want to lead an extraordinary life, find out what the ordinary do–and don't do it.\n\n- Tommy Newberry, Success is Not an Accident: Change Your Choices Change Your Life\n|\nGive away everything—even your heart, soul, and mind. Nothing is yours. Keep your experiences and your memories. Those are yours and they make you who you are.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nNever question another man's motive. His wisdom, yes, but not his motives.\n\n- Dwight\n|\nEvery true scientist is a philosopher, but not every philosopher is a scientist.\n\n- Abhijit\n|\nWe are all connected. When one arm or foot is poisoned, the whole body becomes infected.\n\n- Suzy Kassem, Rise Up and Salute the Sun: The Writings of Suzy Kassem\n|\nI was halfway across America, at the dividing line between the East of my youth and the West of my future.\n\n- Jack Kerouac, On the Road\n|\nThe larger the complex, the more the energy it takes away from us\n\n- Sunday\n|\nIn the beginning there was nothing, which exploded.\n\n- Terry Pratchett, Lords and Ladies\n|\nThe book was blunt and had an honesty about it, whereas the movie was just a beautiful lie.\n\n- Bret Easton Ellis, Imperial Bedrooms\n|\nHold your venomDo you recognise the instinctin me, fellow scorpion?\n\n- Kiera Woodhull, Chaos of the Mind\n|\nBut only a person in the depths of despair neglected to look beyond winter to the spring that inevitably followed, bringing back color and life and hope.\n\n- Mary Balogh, A Matter of Class\n|\nIf you work, you will find favor from God and you will become a rich man\n\n- Sunday"